Hundreds of women in England are to be the first in the world to benefit from a drug for advanced cervical cancer - the most common cancer affecting young women.

Trials show Avastin, which is already used in other cancers, gives women almost four months’ extra life.

The drug will be available to patients via the Cancer Drugs Fund despite not yet having a licence for cervical cancer.

